enigd Koninkrijk","Blankney, Lincolnshire, England":"Blankney, Lincolnshire, England","Park Hall, Morton, Derbyshire, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1235–":"about 1235–Deceased","1235–Female":"1235–Deceased","1203–1268":"1203–1268","1250–1327":"1250–1327","1258–1337":"1258–1337","1265–1300":"1265–1300","–Male":"Deceased","1215–Male":"1215–Deceased","Abt 1235":"about 1235","1250":"1250","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1203":"1203","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","1300":"1300","um 1250":"about 1250","1265":"1265","about 1258":"about 1258","about 1254":"about 1254","Ashover, Derbyshire, England":"Ashover, Derbyshire, England","Harthill, Derbyshire, England":"Harthill, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Blankney, Lincolnshire, England":"Blankney, Lincolnshire, England","Park Hall, Morton, Derbyshire, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Harthill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from any of three places called Harthill (Cheshire, Derbys, and WR Yorks).","2  Scottish: locative name from Harthill near Inverurie (Aberdeens) or, less likely, from the barony of Harthill (Lanarks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Hartell","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Theresia.","English and Scottish: variant of   Hartle  .","Americanized form of German   Hartel   or <b>Härtel</b>."]},{"name":"Hartles","meanings":["English: variant of   Hartle   (  see  Harthill  ) with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Hartill","meanings":["English (Staffordshire) and Scottish: variant of   Hartle  ."]},{"name":"Hartle","meanings":["German (also <b>Härtle</b>): from a pet form of the various ancient Germanic compound names formed with <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’ as the first element.","English (Worcestershire and Staffordshire): habitational name from any of the three places called Harthill (Cheshire, Derbyshire, and Yorkshire), named with Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’.","Scottish: habitational name from Harthill near Inverurie (Aberdeenshire) or, less likely, from the barony of Harthill (Lanarkshire), probably from the same etymology as 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de Harthill was born about 1235, in Harthill, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom as the